  "prompt": "How thoroughly does steak need to be cooked to kill bacteria?",
  "response": "To ensure that bacteria in steak are killed, it is recommended to cook the steak to an internal temperature of at least 145\u00b0F (63\u00b0C). This temperature ensures that harmful bacteria such as E. coli, Salmonella, and other pathogens are effectively eliminated. After reaching this temperature, the steak should then rest for at least 3 minutes, which allows the heat to continue killing any remaining bacteria.\n\nNote that whole cuts of beef, like steak, are generally safer than ground beef, because bacteria typically reside on the surface of the meat. When cooked, the outside of the steak reaches a high enough temperature to kill bacteria, even if the inside remains less cooked. However, ground beef requires a higher internal temperature of 160\u00b0F (71\u00b0C) because bacteria may be mixed throughout the meat during grinding.\n\nAlways use a meat thermometer to ensure the proper internal temperature is reached for safety.",
